g.ns0:text: Rule 0: Constant Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} a =0$\\\\\nRule I: Sum Rule: $\\frac d {dx} (f+g) = \\frac{d}{dx}f + \\frac{d}{dx} g$\\\\\nRule II: Product Rule: $\\frac d {dx} (fg) = \\frac{df}{dx} g + f \\frac{dg}{dx}$

Rule II.a: Scalar Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} af = a \\frac{d}{dx} f$ \\\\\n Rule II.b: Power Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = n \\frac{d}{dx} x^{n-1}$\\\\\n Rule II.c: Quotient Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} \\left ( \\frac f g \\right ) = \\frac{\\frac{df}{dx} g - f \\frac{dg}{dx} }{g^2}$
Rule III: Chain Rule: $\\frac{d}{dx} \\left ( f \\circ g \\right ) = (\\frac{df}{dx}\\circ g ) \\frac{dg}{dx}$
Rule III.a: Inverse Rule: $\\frac d{dx} f^{-1} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{df}{dx} \\circ f^{-1}}$

Let $f$ be a real function.\\\\\nA point $a \\in \\mathbf R$ is an \\emph{point of inflection}\\\\\nif the concavity of $f$ changes at $a$.
A point of inflection is a critical point\\\\\n for $f\'$, but not every critical point of\\\\\n$f\'$ is an inflection point.
